T1  - THE EVENT OF CEO SUCCESSION, PERFORMANCE, AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS
AU  - Osborn, Richard N.
AU  - Jauch, Lawrence R.
AU  - Martin, Thomas N.
AU  - Glueck, William F.
Y1  - 1981/03/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255833
DO  - 10.5465/255833
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 183
EP  - 191
VL  - 24
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses the results of a research which examined the specific aspects of performance and environmental volatility that might be related to the event of executive succession. The authors analyzed data from 313 large industrial firms gathered by ?Fortune?. The authors investigated data that contained information on the market environment, strategy, and performance of organizations. Succession was labeled as either present or absent for each firm against financial performance in terms of return on assets. Thirty one percent of the sample experienced managerial succession. Profits were found to be a weak predictor of executive succession. Divestiture and mergers were found to be significant predictors of succession.
AB  - The article discusses the results of a research which examined the specific aspects of performance and environmental volatility that might be related to the event of executive succession. The authors analyzed data from 313 large industrial firms gathered by ?Fortune?. The authors investigated data that contained information on the market environment, strategy, and performance of organizations. Succession was labeled as either present or absent for each firm against financial performance in terms of return on assets. Thirty one percent of the sample experienced managerial succession. Profits were found to be a weak predictor of executive succession. Divestiture and mergers were found to be significant predictors of succession.
