T1  - A Level Specific Prediction of Spans of Control Examining the Effects of Size, Technology, and Specialization
AU  - Dewar, Robert D.
AU  - Simet, Donald P.
Y1  - 1981/03/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255821
DO  - 10.5465/255821
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 5
EP  - 24
VL  - 24
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This paper develops and tests a model which states in level specific fashion the effects that size, routineness, and the number of different specialties have on the span of control. The number of specialties supervised was found to decrease spans at lower and middle levels and increase them at upper levels. Routineness had little effect at any level. Size had little effect at lower levels but a positive effect at middle ones.
AB  - This paper develops and tests a model which states in level specific fashion the effects that size, routineness, and the number of different specialties have on the span of control. The number of specialties supervised was found to decrease spans at lower and middle levels and increase them at upper levels. Routineness had little effect at any level. Size had little effect at lower levels but a positive effect at middle ones.
